x4freetext: 15UD Pelletron accelerator facility
A pulsed beam of 16O with a pulse separation of 250
ns and pulse width of ~1 ns, in the energy range 75
to 102 MeV, was used in the experiment.
As the beam current was very low for 24Mg in the
required energy range, a DC beam was used in the
measurements energy range 111 to 125 MeV in the
laboratory frame.
Two different set-up were used for two reactions
For 194Pt(16O,f) measurement:
Two large-area, position-sensitive, multiwire
proportional counters (MWPCs) of active area
24 cm x 10 cm were used for fission fragment
measurement, by forming a time-of-flight setup.
These detectors were mounted on the two arms of the
scattering chamber. The forward detector centered at
polar angle 45 deg(azimuthal angle = 90 deg) and the
backward detector centered at 115 deg(azimuthal angle
= 270 deg). The nearest distance to the forward
detector from the target was 56 cm and that to the
backward detector was 30 cm. The target was kept at
45 deg with respect to beam direction. The gas
detectors were operated with isobutane gas at a low
pressure around (3.5 T).
For 186W(24Mg,f) measurement:
The detectors used were slightly smaller with an
active area of 20 cm * 10 cm. The forward detector
was centered at polar angle 38 deg (azimuthal angle =
90 deg) and the backward detector was centered at 113
deg (azimuthal angle = 270 deg). The nearest distance
to the forward detector from the target was 55.5 cm,
and that to the backward detector was 40 cm.
Common set-up for two reactions
Two solid-state detectors, mounted at +- 10 deg
with respect to the beam axis, were used to monitor
and position the beam at the center of the target.
One of these monitors was used to get the time
structure of the beam by generating a TAC signal with
an rf signal.
The fast timing signal from the anode of both
MWPC1 and MWPC2 were used to obtain the TOF of the
fragments with respect to the beam pulse.
These anode signals were processed by constant
fraction discriminators.
A fast coincidence between any of the anode signals
and the rf pulse was used as the master trigger for
the data acquisition system.
The position information of the fragments entering the
detectors was obtained from the delay-line readout of
the wire planes though time of flight was also used
time difference method was mainly used for analysis
purpose.
Statistical error
